column49: The lesson plan submitted included content and language objectives. The teacher introduced the topic of writing pro and con of a particular issue. Teacher indicated:  We are going to continue our work today.  We are going to finish reading two articles on the same topic and write a good argument. Its important to look at bot sides of the argument; we will use this chart. The teacher modeled one example.
column53: Students were partnered and guidelines for note taking reviewed. Students were engaged and their participation encouraged. The teacher made sure to re-direct students' attention when needed. Teacher indicated:  Thank you for working hard today; you showed that you can do it.  Teacher said:  I need all eyes on me.
column57: Students were paired. All handouts and charts were created and distributed during the course of the lesson. Teacher asked:  What is your story about?  What is your understading of the main idea?  Do you agree or disagree?  Why?
column59: The teacher is very reflective.  He takes notes during our briefing and engages in discussion regarding the feedback given.  He expresses ideas of how to improve the delivery of instruction.

column49: This is a stand alone ENL class composed of students in mixed grades (6-8) of various ENL levels.  The teacher planned and delivered a lesson that incorporated differentiated material; however, he had some difficulty in providing equal time and support to both groups.  Teacher indicated:  Everyone on this side will continue te same story as last week. You are to follow the directions (emergent group).  Everybody here (entering level), take out your vocabulary paper.
column53: The teacher provided some assistance to each side of the room with little success. Students were extremely talkative and not working dilligently.  It took too long to get the lesson started.
column57: The two group set up was counterproductive as both groups were not cooperative. The teacher had some difficulty in getting the students engaged.
column59: The teacher is very reflective. He is also frustrated in his lack of expertise in grouping students and not having a written curriculum. Suggestions were given to begin the class first as a whole group and then creating different groups not so much based on their ENL level but on their ability; it was also suggested to be more specific with students in regard to the sequence of the lesson.

column49: This was a second lesson observation on the same day. The teacher used some of the suggestion previously discussed and started the lesson as a whole group.  He was very clear on the sequence of the activities planned. Students had a clear understanding of the expectations.  He conducted an oral assessment of what had been accomplished the previous lesson before proceeding.
column53: Students were engaged and were periodically assessed. The teacher reassured the students by continually asking, Do you have a question for me? The sequence of each activity was introduced and modeled.
column57: Students were encourage to participate throughout the lesson; pacing of each activity was effectively used to allow for student reflection.
column59: The teacher is very reflective and uses given suggetions immediatedly.

column49: The teacher follows the school's testing and curriculum outlines for this grade.  He follows the school's guidelines as far as classroom expectations.  The teacher has serious difficulty with classroom management.
column53: The teacher had lacked consistency of classroom expectation and behavior.  He is easily flustered and reverses his own and those of the school's rules (eating in the classroom, etc).  When he is consistent with the clear expectations needed; the students appear to behave and cooperate but it doesnt last long.  The teacher has many of the pitfalls of new teachers but he needs to accept the feedback and continue working on them.
column57: Instruction is not as consistent and high quality due to students' misbehavior
column59: The teacher is reflective but doesnt always transfers suggestions into successful classroom practices.

column49: There was no instructional objective written anywhere or stated.
column53: only five of 18 students completed the one task which was to graph two linear equations.  All others socialized the entire time.
column57: There was no whole class discussion. The teacher circulated and supported some students. Most students could not do the work and little effort was made to help them get unstuck.
column59: The teacher thought this lesson went well.  He stated that it takes time and students need time.
